Jeremy Corbyn is making his debut on Prime Minister's Questions
Since his election, Mr. Corbyn's debut at PMQ is highly anticipated.
The new Labour leader, Jeremy Corbyn, will make his debut in Prime Minister's Questions later, and for the first time, will be working with David Cameron.
Mr Corbyn will ask the first of his six questions shortly after noon, while his performance is likely to be closely monitored by the media and MPs.
In a weekly statement, he called for "less theater and more facts".
He also said he could skip a few sessions he'd leave to his colleagues.
This meeting will be the first parliamentary test of Mr Corby's leadership following his appointment to the shadow cabinet and his Tuesday address to TUC's annual congress.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to stand silently during the national anthem at the service on Tuesday to mark the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain was met with criticism from a number of Conservative MPs and has been the focus of several newspaper headline stories.
Mr. Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem has attracted attention.
Mr. Corbyn's spokesman said he would "stand in honorable silence" and acknowledge "the heroism of the Royal Air Force in the Battle of Britain".
However, Mr Corbyn's shadow cabinet member Owen Smith told BBC Two's Newsnight that he would recommend that the Labour leader sing the national anthem "regardless" of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Nearly a dozen shadow ministers refused to serve on Mr. Corbyn's top team, citing differences in economics, defense and foreign affairs, and only less than a sixth of parliamentary parties originally supported him as leader.
BBC political correspondent Robin Brant says that political differences in work are also "getting worse" after Mr Corbyn's appointment over his position in the European Union and the government's benefit limit.
Mr Corbyl stated at the TUC conference that the Labour Party had submitted amended proposals to remove the whole idea of the benefit limit.
Hours later, Mr Smith, the secretary of shadow jobs and pensions, said that the party "very clearly" opposed government plans to cut the limit from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader to face David Cameron in the last decade since his election as leader of the Conservatives.
The Labour leader, who promised a different approach to politics, claims he has ideas "out of the crowd" for questions for Mr Cameron and has received more than 30,000 proposals.
MP Islington North says PMQs are too confrontational and that they will refrain from both "post-response" and "busted trade", and instead promise to focus on important issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges young people face.
Mr Corbyn claims that Angela Eagle, the shadow trade secretary, will represent him at PMQ if she doesn't attend, like when Mr Cameron travels abroad.
He also gave up the idea of letting his fellow members speak for him from time to time because he was told he was still discussing the matter with House Speaker John Bercow.
When Mr Cameron became leader in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the "Punch and Judy" style of politics that was often associated with PMQ, but admitted a few years later that he had failed.
Since its first broadcast in 1990, PMQ has been seen as a key barometer of leaders' judgment, their leadership of the House and their stance among other MPs, although critics have argued that they have become a caricature and require far-reaching reforms.
