Multiple sclerosis: Not only depends on the medication, but also on the patient's willingness to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease and a person diagnosed with it needs the care of a number of specialists: a neurologist, a physical therapist, an ergotherapist, a urologist, an ophthalmologist, a psychologist, a psychiatrist, and many other specialists.
However, it is not just about medical care, for example women with multiple sclerosis also need counselling if they decide to have a child, social legal advice, housing recommendations, etc.
Yet, all this is not enough: the patient himself can be profoundly affected by the disease.
The more he actively fights the disease, the longer he can work and the more he may need to make drastic changes to his lifestyle.
As doctors point out, the passivity of the sick leaves room for disease activity.
For example, regular exercise has been shown to significantly delay the time when a patient needs some form of compensatory assistance, such as a stick.
It is important that patients and their environment avoid the myths that the disease automatically leads to their being confined to a wheelchair.
That's why the Give Yourself a Chance website (www.bezmytu.cz) was created, which is supported by the ongoing Give Yourself a Chance media campaign.
The most important person in the care of a sick person with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
In the case of multiple sclerosis, the more the disease is treated, the more the doctor can influence.
That's because we have drugs for multiple sclerosis in an inflammatory stage, when the neurodegeneration process isn't that strong yet.
The sooner we intervene, the more hopeful we are that we will be able to stop the disease and delay disabling, explains Dr. Eva Med of the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
Rehabilitation care is very important for people with multiple sclerosis, which most often addresses lower limb weakness or imbalance.
The patient is treated according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve walking, strengthen the pelvic floor, alleviate swallowing disorders or improve coordination.
"It's really individual, depending on the patient's specific problems", says Dr. Martin Kövári, principal of the Molla Faculty Hospital's Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine Clinic.
Although people with multiple sclerosis have the same disease, each person has a slightly different manifestation.
Rehabilitation can't stop the disease, but it can always ease its symptoms.
However, exercise also boosts the body's immune system, which is desirable in the case of multiple sclerosis.
Another benefit of regular exercise is that the sick person checks their skills, and this increases their confidence.
"Exercise also releases endorphins and makes you feel good", notes Dr. Kamila Řas of the Rehabilitation Clinic of the Faculty Hospital of the Royal Vineyard.
By influencing the physical side, we influence the limbic system responsible for emotions.
It directly interferes with the psyche and immune processes and stabilizes the disease, he adds.
"In the past, these so-called patients were being sparing, but now we know they need a targeted load", says Professor PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Rehabilitation and Physical Medicine Clinic at the Faculty Hospital in Motol.
The goal of physical therapy is to keep a person self-sufficient for as long as possible, including employment.
Physiotherapists therefore work with ergotherapists to provide each person with a compensatory aid tailored to them.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or psychiatrist.
They're in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, most people will shake it.
They're in shock, panic, fear.
He must respond to a great burden - loss of health.
With a soul that's so broken, we should go to someone, not try to carry everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them to finally conclude that even with a disability, a full life can be lived and that sclerosis does not mean the end of life", says psychotherapist Renata Malin-Schubert of the Neurological Clinic of the General Faculty Hospital in Prague.
