Sonogenetics or control of brain cells by sound waves
This video shows how sound pulses affect the direction in which particles move.
Scientists have bred worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves.
Small particles change direction when they are hit by sound pulses that are unheard of by the human ear.
Pulses work by switching on cells of genetically modified motor neurons that are programmed to respond to these ultrasonic waves.
Related: Scientists can read and record brain activity using light
Scientists said that these worms are a fine example of a new method called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart, and muscle cells and activates itself outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that this method could one day replace deep brain stimulation - an invasive procedure in which electrodes are fed into the patient's brain that stimulate the brain.
The noises don't usually respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that the reaction comes when he places them in a liquid containing microscopic bubbles.
He found that bubbles amplify ultrasonic waves that then pass through the worm's body.
The amplified ultrasonic waves act in the TRP-4 ion channels, which are found in the membranes of some worm cells.
Sound waves open and activate the cells to which they are connected, reports Nature Communications.
To control the worms using ultrasonic waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms by making some of their motor neurons contain TRP-4 ion channels.
Then when he used ultrasound on the modified worms, the sound waves were amplified by microbubbles and transferred to the worms, where they turned on the modified motor neurons.
The new method is similar in many ways to optogenetics, a pioneering tool that enables scientists to turn on and off neurons using light.
But Chalasani has been told that sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent by optical fiber to a desired location in the brain, ultrasound waves can penetrate tissue without restriction and be sent directly to the brain.
"We believe that by using gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to ultrasound signals used in clinical treatment to treat neurological diseases", Chalasani said.
He added that the method would also be used to treat muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
