In their most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve lawmakers will spend two days this week sitting at a 27-foot-long Honduran mahogany table deciding whether it's time to raise the key interest rate after nearly a decade.
Overlaid on one end of the central bank's ornament, the two-story meeting room will be a mural painting of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the nation's economic interests above all else.
The central bank has a dual mandate from Congress: maximize American employment and keep prices stable.
But since the Great Recession, Fed officials have recognized that there is an unwritten third term: financial stability.
And this third term could be the X-Factor too close to the predictable decision to be announced on Thursday whether the US economy is ready to launch a move away from an unprecedented stimulus of near-zero short-term interest rates on the spot since late 2008.
While most data show solid economic growth, recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare the already cautious Fed into adding to the volatility by raising its federal funds rate of reference by as little as a quarter of a percentage point.
"It is clear that the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing to watch first", said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
"But I think they were just looking for an excuse not to increase the rate, the increased uncertainty surrounding the global market already giving them enough reason to wait", she said.
There's no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself is a cause of nervousness in the financial markets.
About half of the economists recently interviewed by Blomberg predicted a rate hike this week.
However, the financial markets expect the Fed to delay the issue, with a key indicator of only about a 30% chance of a raise.
That would indicate a stock market decline if the Fed raises rates only if politicians hit a slump with the promise that further increases are in sight.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The meeting was started with the expectation that Fed politicians would slow rates down this week, says John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be a surprise if the Fed raised rates now", he says.
If Fed politicians do, "they should go to extremes in their programming statements and hold the financial markets in their hands to keep them from panicking".
Other experts have argued that raising rates would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about how the Fed would proceed.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed well on its way to raising the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. economic recovery.
Yellen said she expects rates to rise this year through the spring and early summer despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress is needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the labour market experienced solid growth this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% in the previous month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to what the Fed considers full employment.
The payroll gains showed signs of improvement.
And while inflation continues to fall below the central bank's annual target of 2 percent, Fed politicians say the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can and needs higher rates, given the tightness of the labor market", said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world began to shift late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell as much as 16% below its record in May, as investors feared that the slowing Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market has been a bit down this month and the Dow is now losing just about 10% of its May peak.
The uncertain market situation gives the Fed's political actors a complex calculation to take into account the rate increase.
"In the absence of what happened in the financial markets, and reports of weakness in the Chinese economy over the past few weeks, there would be a tightening of this meeting", said Stephen D. Oliner, senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and former Fed official.
Now he predicts they'll wait at least a month to gain better control of the consequences.
"There is a lot of uncertainty about the impact this will have on the U.S. economy, and they have almost no data to rely on for the latest developments in China", Oliner said.
The health of the global economy is not a key concern of the Fed, so it should not technically be included in its decision-making.
But the Fed has actually become the monetary authority of the entire world.
The central bank's influence in recent years has been enormous.
Just a hint by then-President Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could "squeeze" their monetary expansion into the marketplace triggered worldwide crunch.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly interconnected, Fed officials can be expected to monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central bankers and experts to better understand the state of the global economy.
Their decision-making process is "more art than science", said Zachary Karabell, global wealth management strategy director at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., noted this month that "the Fed has a history of exaggerated movements in financial markets that seem to be inconsistent with economic fundamentals".
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee's policy-making body who pushed for higher rates, cited the 1998-99 decision as an example.
The Asian financial crisis led the Fed to cut its benchmark rate by 0.75 percentage points over three sessions "despite limited identifiable impacts on growth in the U.S"., Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed reversed these cuts.
The Fed should only prioritize concerns about financial stability during a major crisis, such as the 2008 market crash, said Adam Posen S., a former member of the Bank of England's rate-setting committee.
The latest outbreak is not even close to this level, he said.
"You certainly don't want to be in a situation of fear of rising rates because markets have become angry", said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act has a second mandate and it doesn't mention financial stability, and until that changes, I don't think they should be on top.
