For mildly obese diabetics, weight loss surgery may be helpful.
The benefits of weight loss surgery for slightly obese people with type 2 diabetes can last for at least five years, according to a new study.
However, it is too early to tell whether mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes live longer after weight loss surgery than those who receive non-surgical treatment.
"The mortality data take a long time to show", says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote the introduction to a new JAMA surgical study.
Weight loss surgery, bariatric surgery, uses different methods to shrink the stomach.
Reducing hunger and limiting the human body's ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the research has been done in people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 25 or higher.
BMI, which measures the weight-to-height ratio, is considered normal at between 18.5 and 24.9.
BMI of 25 or higher indicates an individual is overweight and people over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For their new studies, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected from a 2007 study that looked at two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and gastriectomy - in treatment procedures for type 3 diabetes in people who were slightly obese.
The average BMI of those who had surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of their fifth year, according to the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of those who had not received surgery for diabetes remained roughly the same at 29.
Among the patients who had surgery, diabetes was completely resolved in 36 percent and partially resolved in 28 cases.
In the medicated group, only 1% of patients were completely and only 2% were partially treated for diabetes.
Furthermore, control of blood pressure, trigylcerides, and "bad" LDL cholesterol was shown to be "generally better in the surgical group", the authors found.
The researchers also monitored the patient's blood hemoglobin A1c levels, which reflect the body's continuous blood sugar levels.
The best way to keep hemoglobin A1c below 7 percent, the researchers say.
After the operation, the average hemoglobin A1c dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the treated group, this value remained at about 8%.
But this improved "glycemic control" - which is reflected in better hemoglobin levels of A1c - did not reduce mortality within five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results with two types of operations.
After the fifth year, the bypass group lost more weight compared to the gastriectomy group (18.7 to 14.2 kg), achieved greater decreases in BMI (7.4 to 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1 percent to 2.1 percent) and were more likely to have diabetes remission (46.9 percent to 16.7 percent).
While the new study shows no improvement in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of stronger people in Sweden, where they found that surgery leads to longer life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona College of Medicine-Phoenix.
According to a Swedish study, obese people who had bariatric surgery had about a 29 percent greater chance of survival over the next 15 years than the group who had tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not show any improvement in survival among patients after surgery, Blackstone says this is a reassuring result for people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in these procedures.
"This is where this work is critical, because it says surgery is safer in the lower BMI group", without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
