Xi calls for opening up the economy to the wider world
It is necessary to open up the economy to the wider world to boost growth, President Xi Jinping told the group, whose task is to reform governance on Tuesday.
"China should engage in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improve open policies", he said of the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group for the Deepening of Overall Reform.
Promoting openness in the emerging reforms will add new impetus and vitality, as well as provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Governing Group adopted a number of directives, including a negative list of regulatory market access, the relaxation of border control policies, the support to state-owned enterprises (SOEs) to absorb private capital and the reorganisation of the registration system of residents.
The statement states that a negative list will be drawn up identifying sectors and enterprises that are outside the investment ceilings.
This system will be progressively tested and improved through test programmes.
This step is significant because it will give the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a legal business environment and making the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also release controls on the powers it delegates to companies and make sure that companies themselves decide how to run their business.
The statement also states that China will enable border regions to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to support regional growth.
In an effort to open up the state-controlled sector, more areas will be opened up for private investment.
"The Government will not change its foreign investment policy and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services", the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a green card, thanks to the optimisation of requirements and simplification of the application process.
The meeting also discussed ensuring the rights of lawyers to practice and develop professional judges and prosecutors.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and the CEOs Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
A new bedroom may be established in the Karlovy Vary region.
According to the Deputy Head of the Karlovy Vary Region, Jakub Panick (ČSSD), the current capacity of the bed departments of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between the departments of the individual hospitals.
But there are also opportunities to expand care in the region.
For example, a day surgery center could be established in the surgical department, where, according to the design, surgical procedures that do not require hospitalization for more than 24 hours would be performed.
The specific hospitals where one-day surgery should be done are not yet clear.
In the leather department of Karlovy Vary Hospital, a laser centre could be set up with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases.
Concepcion also recommended the creation of an Appalachian Center to care for patients with brain impairment who are in a vegetative state.
Such a centre should be centrally established and should be an integral part of the anaesthetic-resuscitation unit.
There is also the possibility of concentrating such a facility in an Island hospital where similar care already exists.
Another bed capacity which appears to be insufficient in the Karlovy Vary region is the follow-up beds, in particular the LDN beds, which are insufficient in Nejdk and should be closely linked to the acute care beds.
Part of this facility should function as a rehabilitation bed and part as a classic LDN bed, the concept recommends.
As he points out, the beds for follow-up care are missing mainly at Karlovy Vary Hospital.
They could use abandoned buildings after centralization.
Last but not least, there are no social care beds in Karlovy Vary focusing on the treatment of Alzheimer's disease.
These beds are scarce throughout the republic, so they could be used for other regions as an Alzheimer's center.
The recommendation also calls for hospitals to prepare for the deployment of so-called beds to be used for which European grants will be made available.
"These are beds that will follow the areas of specialized care and will provide space for translating patients after surgery, such as cardiosurgery, neurosurgery, transplantation or other procedures", describes the Regional Concept of Bed Care.
New services could also be offered in the field of psychiatric care.
